{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #962: declared status 'open'. Formalized: yes. Let $k(n)$ be the maximal $k$ such that there exists $m\\leq n$ such that each of the integers\\[m+1,\\ldots,m+k\\]are divisible by at least one prime $>k$. Estimate $k(n)$. Current best: Erd\\H{o}s \\cite{Er65} wrote it is 'not hard to prove' that\\[k(n)\\gg_\\epsilon \\exp((\\log n)^{1/2-\\epsilon})\\]and it 'seems likely' that $k(n)=o(n^\\epsilon)$, but had no non-trivial upper bound for $k(n)$. Tang has proved a lower bound of\\[k(n)\\geq \\exp\\left(\\left(\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}-o(1)\\right)\\sqrt{\\log n\\log\\log n}\\right).\\]  References  [Er65] Erd\\H{o}s, P., Extremal problems in number theory. Prize: no. OEIS: A327909. Tags: number theory.","id":"vf_30fc0175e85918f6","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos962.erdos_962 https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos962.erdos_962.","id":"vf_564c95e23fe055d0","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/962.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_30fc0175e85918f6","source_root":"sha256:1faedc24f040a60a22177b456c74b969a61ce8836082297b1835797a57b4fa56","target":"erdos:962","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_564c95e23fe055d0","source_root":"sha256:1faedc24f040a60a22177b456c74b969a61ce8836082297b1835797a57b4fa56","target":"erdos:962","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Materialized typed link between accepted findings.","inferred":true,"relation":"synthesized_from","source":"vf_564c95e23fe055d0","source_root":"sha256:1faedc24f040a60a22177b456c7